<subSubSection id="06C7E7B36A6ED6E4B3F980C6B6EC9D83" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph id="63B00B6FC6823F1577818621BB0E9B2B" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">The present species was described after a specimen from East Africa; the type (no. 183/47) is still present in the Collection.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9E8CA5E55A2161BD0167B98799C1DFB7" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="91D7589F850319749806D27C845DFA53" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
Berlese compares the species with 
<taxonomicName id="77207D779EEE1635368A81EC93E36018" class="Arachnida" family="Phthiracaridae" genus="Steganacarus" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="magnus">magnus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="0ECE15B47084D54DB6A2740DC149C01A" class="Arachnida" family="Phthiracaridae" genus="Steganacarus" genus.completionEvidence="missing" genus.completionRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sarcoptiformes" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anomalus">anomalus</taxonomicName>
and in general shape it reminds indeed of these species. The notogastral hairs are, however, very small, hardly visible, slightly pointing backwards, and irregularly curved. The type-specimen is closed (as Berlese mentioned already); the colour is dark-brown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
